                            <comment id="12992118" author="chmorgan" created="Tue, 8 Feb 2011 19:14:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;TestServer.py was creating the TServerSocket() with a single parameter, the port number 9090. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;TServerSocket was altered to look like:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;class TServerSocket(TSocketBase, TServerTransportBase):&lt;br/&gt;
  &quot;&quot;&quot;Socket implementation of TServerTransport base.&quot;&quot;&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;  def _&lt;em&gt;init&lt;/em&gt;_(self, host=None, port=9090, unix_socket=None):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;so the call in TestServer.py was passing 9090 as the &apos;host&apos; argument. This was a side effect of &lt;a href=&quot;http://svn.apache.org/viewvc?view=revision&amp;amp;revision=1063806&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://svn.apache.org/viewvc?view=revision&amp;amp;revision=1063806&lt;/a&gt; which changed the TServerSocket constructor.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Fix the issue by adding a host value of &quot;None&quot; to the constructor which shifts the port to the port argument of the constructor.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Tests run better after the change.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12992170" author="roger.meier" created="Tue, 8 Feb 2011 20:46:36 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks Chris!&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;committed.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
